# .clinerules
# liquidity-bot-v2 — Cline agent standing rules
# Last updated: Sprint 22D

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# EXECUTION MODEL
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

## What Cline does
- Writes and edits files only
- Runs git add, git status, git commit
- Runs fast, local-only Python one-liners (no network, no I/O longer than 5s)
- Reads files to confirm edits landed before posting a confirm message

## What Cline never does
- Never executes any command that makes an HTTP/network request
- Never runs scripts/fetch.py, scripts/run_backtest.py, or scripts/sweep.py
- Never runs curl, wget, or any shell command that contacts an external API
- Never chains commands with && where the second depends on a long-running first
- Never executes a command that could run longer than 5 seconds

## Handoff steps
- Any step requiring a network call or long-running process must be written
  as a [YOU RUN] step with the exact command the developer will paste into
  their terminal
- Cline waits at every [YOU RUN] step until the developer pastes output back
  before continuing to the next step

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# CHECK SCRIPTS
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

- All network validation lives in scripts/check_*.py files
- Cline writes these scripts; the developer runs them
- Every check script must:
    - Load .env via python-dotenv (wrapped in try/except ImportError)
    - Use urllib with an explicit timeout (never omit timeout=)
    - Print a single final line: CHECK PASSED: <what> or CHECK FAILED: <why>
    - Exit with code 0 on pass, code 1 on fail
- Check scripts are prerequisites: fetch.py is never run without
  check_graph_endpoint.py passing first

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# STRUCTURED SUMMARY BLOCKS
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

- Every script that produces data output (fetch.py, run_backtest.py,
  sweep.py) must end with a clearly delimited summary block:
    print("=== <SCRIPT NAME> SUMMARY ===")
    ... one line per key metric ...
    print("<SCRIPT NAME> COMPLETE.")
- This block is what the developer pastes back for collaborator review
- Never require the developer to open a JSON file to confirm success —
  all pass/fail signal must be visible in terminal output

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# CODE STANDARDS
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

- All financial values use Decimal, never float
  (float permitted only at display/serialization boundaries)
- Atomic writes only: write to .tmp then os.replace(), never write
  directly to a final path
- No hardcoded pool addresses or token symbols in business logic —
  read from registry/registry.json
- Never use text-based find/replace on any JSON file —
  always write a Python script that reads, patches in memory,
  asserts structure, then writes atomically

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# MEMORY FILE RULES
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

- memory/activeContext.md, memory/known_issues.md, and
  memory/manifest.json are the source of truth for project state
- Any commit that changes a script's status, sprint, or behavior
  must also update all three memory files in the same commit
- manifest.json must always be valid JSON after any edit —
  validate with: python3 -c "import json; json.load(open('memory/manifest.json')); print('VALID')"
  before committing
- Never allow memory files to describe a sprint that is behind
  the actual git log

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# SPEC EXECUTION RULES
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

- Allow full thinking — never suppress reasoning or use shorthand
  directives that skip self-consistency checks
- Number every step; each step names an exact file path and exact tool
- After every read step, post a heartbeat confirm before proceeding:
  e.g. "FETCH.PY READ. _http_post headers dict confirmed."
- After every edit step, re-read the modified lines to confirm the
  change landed — never trust the edit tool output alone
- Keep each step narrow: one file, one concern
  (large files + multi-edit steps cause context saturation and truncation)
- Smoke test must show real output (N > 0) before any commit that
  touches data fetch or schema logic — never commit on a warning-only run

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────
# COMMIT RULES
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────

- Never commit unless all of the following are true:
    [ ] Edited files re-read and confirmed correct
    [ ] memory/manifest.json validated as valid JSON
    [ ] activeContext.md sprint label matches actual completed work
    [ ] Any [YOU RUN] steps that gate the commit have returned
        output that was reviewed and confirmed PASSED
- Commit message format:
    <VERB> <file(s)>: <one-line description>. Sprint <ID> <status>.
  Examples:
    "FIX fetch.py: Cloudflare-compatible headers. Sprint 22D complete."
    "ADD check_graph_endpoint.py + check_data_files.py. Sprint 22D handoff-ready."